article.headline: Garnett has 31 points, 13 rebounds in win
article.story:
DENVER (AP) -- Flip Saunders tried to downplay his All-Star game coaching assignment. Kevin Garnett did his best to play it up. "We got Flip to the All-Star game," Garnett said after Minnesota's 97-95 victory over Denver on Monday night. "It's a great accomplishment for him and his staff." With the victory, Saunders wrapped up the Western Conference coaching spot in the All-Star game on Feb. 15 in Los Angeles. Although Sacramento can catch Minnesota for the best winning percentage in the conference through the Feb. 1 cutoff, Kings coach Rick Adelman is not eligible to coach the All-Stars in consecutive seasons. "All that means is that a team is winning, and that's the important thing," Saunders said. "It was our 16th road win -- we are 16-7 on the road -- and that's quite a statement for the players and the character of the guys we have in there." Garnett had 31 points and 13 rebounds, and Latrell Sprewell tipped in a missed shot with 16 seconds left to spark the Timberwolves. Sam Cassell added 22 points and 11 assists, and Sprewell had 13 points to help Minnesota push its winning streak to five games and extend Denver's losing streak to a season-worst three games. Minnesota is 22-4 since Dec. 1 after opening the season 9-8. Andre Miller had a triple-double for Denver with 24 points, 10 rebounds and 10 assists. Earl Boykins added 18 points, Chris Andersen 15 and Carmelo Anthony 14. "I thought the key was that with about 4{ minutes to go, we put our three-quarter press on," Saunders said. "I thought that changed the tempo of the game to our favor. We made them less aggressive, and we were able to contest some of their shots." Minnesota got two baskets down the stretch on second- and third-chance chance shots, which Denver coach Jeff Bzdelik called critical. "We had them on the ropes," Bzdelik said, "and it's a shame that fundamentally we just failed to block people out." The Timberwolves, who rallied from a nine-point deficit in the final period, outscored Denver 7-1 in the final 1:36. Minnesota trailed 90-82 before mounting an 8-0 run, including a pair of 3-pointers by Fred Hoiberg, for a 90-90 tie with 3:22 remaining. Miller hit two free throws, and Anthony made a fast-break layup on a feed from Miller for a 94-90 lead. Minnesota's Gary Trent made two free throws, and Garnett tied it again with a jump hook with 48 seconds left. After Boykins missed a 3-point try, Minnesota went ahead when Sprewell tipped in Garnett's missed jumper for a 96-94 lead. "I thought it (Garnett's shot) was in," Sprewell said. "I was just trying to get to the basket in case it popped out, and it did. It came out on my side, and I put it back in the basket. It put us in a position to win." Anthony made one of two free throws with 8.3 seconds left, and Hoiberg did the same for the Timberwolves with 6.6 seconds to go. Miller then missed a 3-pointer as time expired. Minnesota went on an early 9-0 run while Denver shot 1-of-8, and the Timberwolves took an 11-3 lead. Cassell, who had nine points in the quarter, hit back-to-back baskets, and Mark Madsen added a rebound layup as the Timberwolves scored the last six points of the period for a 28-19 lead. Garnett's turnaround jumper gave Minnesota an 11-point lead early in the second quarter, but the Nuggets rallied behind Boykins, who had 10 points in the quarter. Denver shot 65 percent in the period. Boykins' driving layup ignited a 19-4 flurry, giving Denver a 40-36 lead. During the surge, Anthony had a 3-point basket and also stole the ball from Sprewell and made a slam dunk on the other end. Cassell's three straight baskets highlighted an 8-0 run late in the period, and Minnesota led 49-48 at intermission. The Nuggets shot 52 percent in the third quarter to offset 16 points by Garnett. Andersen's tip-in and Boykins' fast-break layup made it 75-70 entering the final period.

Game notes
Nuggets shooting guard Voshon Lenard didn't play because of a strained right quadriceps. ... Minnesota center Ervin Johnson returned to the team after missing the previous two games because of a death in his family. ... Hoiberg will fly from Denver to Lincoln, Neb., Tuesday morning to attend the funeral of his grandfather. He will rejoin the team in time for Wednesday night's game at Golden State.
